                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*teFxkP6bBzLTMwaO 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*teFxkP6bBzLTMwaO 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*teFxkP6bBzLTMwaO 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*teFxkP6bBzLTMwaO 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*teFxkP6bBzLTMwaO 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*teFxkP6bBzLTMwaO 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*teFxkP6bBzLTMwaO 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/0*teFxkP6bBzLTMwaO 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/0*teFxkP6bBzLTMwaO 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/0*teFxkP6bBzLTMwaO 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/0*teFxkP6bBzLTMwaO 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/0*teFxkP6bBzLTMwaO 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/0*teFxkP6bBzLTMwaO 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/0*teFxkP6bBzLTMwaO 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/0*teFxkP6bBzLTMwaO"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">Photo by <a href="https://unsplash.com/@asthetik?utm_source=medium&utm_medium=referral" target="_self">Mike Kenneally</a> on <a href="https://unsplash.com?utm_source=medium&utm_medium=referral" target="_self">Unsplash</a></p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><span>T</span>he average American adult ingests 173 mg of caffeine per day, which is roughly the amount in two 8-oz. cups of coffee. That’s according to <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2072-6643/8/3/154" target="_self">a 2016 study</a> from researchers at the University of Washington in Seattle.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">That UW study is full of interesting nuggets. It found that while caffeine consumption doesn’t correspond with education levels, it <em>does</em> align with income: as average caffeine intake goes up, so does annual pay.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Perhaps a windfall is coming my way, but so far my three daily cups haven’t made me wealthy. I’m still hoping they’ve enriched my health. I hope this because a lot of research has linked coffee consumption to an impressive array of benefits.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Habitual coffee (and tea) drinkers seem to enjoy some protection <a href="https://journals.plos.org/plosmedicine/article?id=10.1371/journal.pmed.1003830" target="_self">from stroke and dementia</a>. Compared to non-drinkers, they’re also <a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S1050173821000888" target="_self">less likely to develop</a> coronary heart disease, cardiovascular disease, and metabolic diseases, including hypertension and type 2 diabetes. There’s even <a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/mnfr.201300526" target="_self">evidence</a> that coffee helps prevents some cancers.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">But what’s the ideal amount for my health? And how late in the day can I drink coffee without messing up my sleep? These are the questions I set out to answer.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4">‘Unfiltered coffee can increase blood cholesterol levels, so filtered coffee is healthiest.’</p></blockquote></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><a href="https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/profile/walter-c-willett/" target="_self">Walter Willett, MD</a>, is a professor of epidemiology and nutrition at the Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health. For <a href="https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMra1816604" target="_self">a 2020 research review</a> in the <em>New England Journal of Medicine, </em>Willett and his coauthors examined the relationship between coffee and health. When I asked him how much coffee is optimal, he gave me a straightforward answer: “About three-to-five [8-oz.] cups per day.”</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If you’re drinking less than that — a cup or two — there doesn’t seem to be a big advantage in upping your intake. However, if you’re drinking much more than that — anything north of 400 mg of caffeine per day— you may want to cut back to avoid potential adverse effects, his research shows. (It’s worth noting that some coffees contain more caffeine than others. For example, <a href="https://www.starbucks.com/menu/product/873068625/hot/nutrition" target="_self">certain Starbucks blends</a> pack more than 400 mg into a single venti-sized cup.)</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Willett appended a few more caveats. “Pregnant and lactating women should keep intake low or avoid caffeine,” he said. “Unfiltered coffee can increase blood cholesterol levels, so filtered coffee is healthiest.”</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">I’d heard this before about unfiltered coffee. I didn’t think to ask him at the time, but later I wondered whether unfiltered coffee is associated with health risks in countries where people drink a lot of it.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">I put this question to one of his coauthors on that 2020 research review. “There is limited evidence from Norwegian cohorts that unfiltered coffee is associated with higher cardiovascular mortality than filtered coffee,” said <a href="https://publichealth.gwu.edu/departments/exercise-and-nutrition-sciences/rob-van-dam" target="_self">Rob van Dam, PhD</a>, a professor at the Milken Institute School of Public Health at George Washington University. “It seems prudent for individuals with higher cholesterol levels to switch from unfiltered to filtered coffee.”</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">I asked van Dam whether coffee-related jitters are anything to worry about. My three cups are at the lower end of the “optimal” range, but I still sometimes get so caffeinated that I feel shaky and amped up. Van Dam said he wasn’t aware of any work linking coffee jitters to health problems. “However,” he added, “it is sensible for coffee consumers to adapt their habitual consumption patterns to avoid unpleasant symptoms.”</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4">‘A lot of sleep clinicians and even scientists will say to cut out caffeine in the afternoon altogether, but I think that is a bit extreme.’</p></blockquote></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Finally, to answer my “how late is too late” question, I emailed with <a href="https://www.henryford.com/physician-directory/d/drake-christopher" target="_self">Christopher Drake, PhD</a>, a professor of medicine at Michigan State University and director of sleep research at Henry Ford Health in Detroit.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">“A lot of sleep clinicians and even scientists will say to cut out caffeine in the afternoon altogether, but I think that is a bit extreme,” he told me.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Drake has conducted <a href="https://jcsm.aasm.org/doi/abs/10.5664/jcsm.3170" target="_self">research</a> on the effects of caffeine at different timepoints leading up to sleep. “Any time after five p.m. is likely to impact sleep, and it may happen even earlier if you are what we call a ‘slow metabolizer’ of caffeine,” he said. (Unfortunately, he said there’s no way for me to know whether I’m a slow metabolizer without taking a specific medical test.)</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">But what about having a cup at one or two in the afternoon — that drowsy stretch after lunch when I could really use it? Drake said that as long as I’m avoiding coffee for at least six-to-eight hours before my bedtime, a cup in the early afternoon shouldn’t interfere with my sleep.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Sleep aside, he pointed out that a cup of coffee late in the day — for example, during a long drive— could save your life by keeping you awake at the wheel. In other words, don’t be so rigid about your coffee intake that you put your health in more-immediate peril.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">It’s rare in this world to be able to have as much of something as you want, and for <em>that</em> amount to be ideal for your health. It seems that with coffee, most drinkers can have their habitual few cups <em>and</em> capture most or all of the drink’s health benefits. Just go easy on the cream and skip the sugar.</p></div></div></div></section><?php include_once 'Elemental/footer.php'; ?>